An American, two classes of citizens
New York - At the time I was writing this article, officials across the United States are still tallying the votes of the 2020 United States presidential election.
Once the final counting results are confirmed, recounts and legal challenges are sure to follow.
In this fiercely competitive and record-breaking election, this is to be expected.
Only American citizens can vote for the President of the United States, but this choice affects people in every place.
If it is said that it is too early to confirm the election results now, then, discussing this election's implications for the strongest country in the world is not too early.
From a positive perspective, the United States is still a powerful democratic country.
Despite the actual restrictions related to the pandemic, the voter participation rate is still very high.
This process seems to be proceeding as planned.
And violent events are rare.
The court is investigating the decision of the United States Postal Service department, which seems to be motivated by politics, obstructing the delivery of ballots from areas where the main votes are expected to come from the Democratic Party.
U.S. President Biden announced his victory on Tuesday evening without basis, almost with no response, and his request to stop counting (at least in those states where he is leading) seems to be ignored.
However, it is worrisome that the divisions among U.S. voters are still very large.
The ballots of the two candidates are almost equal.
Not surprisingly, this division is likely to lead to a split government.
If the current trend continues, the Democratic Party will win the White House and continue to control the House of Representatives, while the Republican Party will continue to control the Senate.
The seats of governors and state legislatures are almost evenly divided between the two parties (with the Republicans having a slight advantage).
The expected "blue wave" by the Democrats did not materialize.
Biden is likely to win the general election with a large margin, possibly winning around 4-5 million votes out of nearly 160 million.
However, the Republicans have held many seats that were predicted to be turned around in the Senate, while the Democrats have actually lost seats in the House of Representatives.
This result is not derived from hard authorization, nor is it from a political adjustment.
Trump's poll situation is very good, with 50 million more votes obtained than in 2016, the second most votes in the history of all presidential candidates in the United States, and more than any previous winner.
Notably, this is happening in the background of a new high in daily cases of over 1 million and over 1,000 deaths, a new high in history.
At a time when the consequences of his government's mishandling of the epidemic have become most severe, nearly half of the voters have switched to support him.
Even if Trump lost, it seems very likely, but he would still have a strong voice, especially if he continues to stay in the public eye (which also seems possible).
Even if he himself does not participate in the election, he is likely to have a significant impact on the choice of Republican nominees in the 2024 presidential election.
The Republican Party will be far removed from the party of former Presidents Bush or Reagan.
Trumpism — a modern American populism — will still be a powerful force.
As expected, despite Trump having no evidence, he will strenuously portray himself as noble and upright, and try to invalidate the election result and accuse vote tampering.
Many of his supporters will refuse to accept the legitimacy of Biden as President.
Trump will probably never concede and certainly not attend the successor's inauguration ceremony.
As Will Rogers said, Trump has never encountered a norm he couldn't break.
Americans are increasingly living in different worlds.
They categorically divide themselves into different communities and regions based on similar viewpoints.
Each world tends to watch its own cable TV channels, listen to its own radio stations and podcasts, and visit its own websites.
While the national citizen curriculum is lacking, it has provided an easy way for the differentiation of different age groups.
It's worth emphasizing that the country's differentiation is not typically divided along economic lines in most cases.
People from different levels all voted for the two candidates, and the voting patterns by population, gender, and race did not turn out to be one-sided as many people had predicted.
Their differences are mainly due to the measures of mitigation.
Clearly, educational level is an indicator of political orientation, and geographical location is also the same. Republican voters tend to live in suburban and rural areas, while Democratic voters tend to live in metropolitan areas.
However, culture may have a larger impact on American politics than any other factor.
In fact, foreign policy does not seem to be very important in the campaign, except for mobilizing specific constituencies, such as the large Cuban and Venezuelan communities in southern Florida.
In this context, it is difficult to obtain public support for major reforms to the presidential election process or the way the government operates.
This situation is no different from the reform of the United Nations Security Council.
Many people believe that the current system has serious flaws and lacks representation, but it is impossible to reach a consensus on reform because any potential solution will benefit some people while harming others.
It's no surprise that those who stand to lose from the change will resist it.
This will make governance more difficult.
This will largely depend on the measure of Mitch McConnell, the Republican leader of the Senate, and his ability and willingness to cooperate with the subsequent Biden administration.
Collaboration will also require Biden to make concessions, which will undoubtedly be resisted by members of his own party with strong ideological views.
The Democrats have tried to denounce everything represented by Trump in a sharp manner.
But they failed.
The Republicans sought an election that would legitimize Trump.
But it also did not meet their wishes.
On the contrary, the election revealed a country and two types of citizens.
They would have to coexist; but whether they could coexist, remains to be seen.
